<h2>Utah Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Utah offers a comprehensive array of incentives that make solar panel and HVAC system installations financially attractive for residents and businesses. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit on the total installed cost of solar systems, including equipment, labor, and permitting fees, through 2032. This credit can be claimed against federal income taxes owed and can be carried forward to future tax years if the credit exceeds current year tax liability. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this translates to \$6,000 in federal tax savings.</p>

<p>At the state level, Utah offers the Renewable Energy Tax Credit, which provides an additional tax credit for residential renewable energy systems. The credit equals 25% of the system cost or \$1,600, whichever is less, making it valuable for smaller installations. Utah also maintains sales tax exemptions for solar energy systems, saving customers an additional 4.85% to 8.35% depending on local tax rates. The state's property tax exemption ensures that adding solar panels won't increase property tax assessments, preserving long-term savings.</p>

<p>Rocky Mountain Power, Utah's primary utility, administers several programs that support renewable energy and efficiency upgrades. The Schedule 136 net metering program allows solar customers to receive retail rate credits for excess energy exported to the grid, though new customers are subject to export compensation at avoided cost rates. The utility also offers the wattsmart programs, providing rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, smart thermostats, and energy-efficient appliances. Heat pump rebates through Rocky Mountain Power range from \$300-800 depending on efficiency ratings, while smart thermostat rebates provide up to \$100 per unit.</p>

<p>Local municipalities across Utah provide additional incentives, with Salt Lake City offering expedited permitting for solar installations and reduced permit fees. Many cities participate in Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing programs, allowing property owners to finance renewable energy and efficiency improvements through special assessments paid with property taxes over 15-20 year terms. These programs eliminate upfront costs and transfer the payment obligation to future property owners if the home is sold.</p>

